did.unittitle: Stanford University, Commission of Engineers, records
did.abstract: The records of the Commission of Engineers, dating from 1906 to 1908, include correspondence, daily journal, estimates of repairs, reports, photographs, and negatives.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Commission of Engineers was charged with directing the restoration of the university's buildings after the earthquake of April 1906. The Commission, composed of Professors Charles D. Marx (civil engineering), Charles B. Wing (structural engineering), and William F. Durand (mechanical engineering), was appointed by the Board of Trustees in June 1906.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Records of the University's Commission of Engineers responsible for the reconstruction of Stanford University buildings after the 1906 earthquake. Includes correspondence, the Commission's daily journals, photographs, negatives, and estimates of repairs.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The original group of records, Box 1 through Box 5, folder 4, were processed in January 1965. Additional progress reports in Box 5, folders 5 and 6, were added in May 1972. In March 1995, the photographic negatives and prints in Boxes 6 through 13 were added to the records.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Related materials may be found in SC 27 (Board of Trustees Supporting Documents), Box 1, folder for August 1, 1906, and in SC 28 (Horace Davis papers), Box 5, folder 37.

accessrestrict.head: Information about Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

userestrict.p: All requests to reproduce, publish, quote from, or otherwise use collection materials must be submitted in writing to the Head of Special Collections and University Archives, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, California 94304-6064. Consent is given on behalf of Special Collections as the owner of the physical items and is not intended to include or imply permission from the copyright owner. Such permission must be obtained from the copyright owner, heir(s) or assigns. See: http://library.stanford.edu/depts/spc/pubserv/permissions.html.
Restrictions also apply to digital representations of the original materials. Use of digital files is restricted to research and educational purposes.
